### Summary

`utf8::is_valid()` returns `false` for valid ASCII strings when compiled with Clang 20 using `-std=c++20`. 
The function incorrectly identifies valid UTF-8 as invalid.

Environment: Clang 20, C++20, utfcpp v4.0.9

### Reproducer

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include "utf8.h"

int main() {
    const char* s1 = "Hi";
    const char* s2 = "Hello";
    const char* s3 = "";

    std::cout << "is_valid(\"Hi\"): " << utf8::is_valid(s1) << "\n";      // Expected: 1, Actual: 0
    std::cout << "is_valid(\"Hello\"): " << utf8::is_valid(s2) << "\n";   // Expected: 1, Actual: 0
    std::cout << "is_valid(\"\"): " << utf8::is_valid(s3) << "\n";        // Expected: 1, Actual: 1

    // Inspect internal behavior
    const char* invalid = utf8::find_invalid(s1);
    std::cout << "first invalid byte: 0x"
              << std::hex << (int)(unsigned char)*invalid << std::dec << "\n";

    if (utf8::is_valid(s1) && utf8::is_valid(s2) && utf8::is_valid(s3)) {
        std::cout << "\n[PASS] All tests passed\n";
        return 0;
    } else {
        std::cout << "\n[FAIL] Bug confirmed!\n";
        return 1;
    }
}
```

#### Expected Output:

```
is_valid("Hi"): 1
is_valid("Hello"): 1
is_valid(""): 1
first invalid byte: 0x0

[PASS] All tests passed
```

#### Actual Output:

```
is_valid("Hi"): 0
is_valid("Hello"): 0
is_valid(""): 1
first invalid byte: 0x48   <-- 'H' is incorrectly flagged as invalid!

[FAIL] Bug confirmed!
```

### Cause

The bug is in the `is_overlong_sequence()` function in `source/utf8/core.h`.
The function uses `if` instead of `else if`, 
causing all conditions to be evaluated even when a previous condition has already matched.

For ASCII char `'H'` (cp=0x48, length=1):
1. first check: `cp < 0x80` is true, but `length == 1`, so we don't return
2. second check: `cp < 0x800` is true (72 < 2048), and `length != 2`, so returns `true`
This is incorrectly marking valid ASCII as "overlong".

### Patch

```cpp
inline bool is_overlong_sequence(utfchar32_t cp, int length)
{
    if (cp < 0x80) {
        if (length != 1)
            return true;
    }
    else if (cp < 0x800) {      // FIXED
        if (length != 2)
            return true;
    }
    else if (cp < 0x10000) {    // FIXED
        if (length != 3)
            return true;
    }
    return false;
}
```

Sorry. This whole issue was inflicted by a clang-tidy run (return early optimization).

Hi, besides the length of the utf8 string I also need to truncate utf8 string if it exceeds utf8 limit.
I didn't find a method in your library and `advance` + `distance` is the closest I found. I suspect I could also wrap into utf8 iterators.
What would you recommend? Would you mind to add something similar to `substr`/`trim`/`truncate`?

```cpp
    auto truncate = [](std::string& string, ptrdiff_t limit) -> std::string& {
        if (utf8::distance(string.begin(), string.end()) > limit) {
            auto new_end = string.begin();
            utf8::advance(new_end, limit, string.end());

            string.resize(new_end - string.begin());
        }

        return string;
    };
```

https://github.com/nemtrif/utfcpp/blob/65701fe00700577f9f4e9b96d682bd7cfcc0b76e/source/utf8/core.h#L132-L146

There is a substantial optimization opportunity here. You could could the number of leading `1` bits using `std::countl_one` (at least in C++20). Then:
```cpp
switch (std::countl_one(*lead_it)) {
case 0: return 1;
case 2: return 2;
case 3: return 3;
case 4: return 4;
default: return 0; // continuation or more than 4 leading 1s
}
```
This should be highly beneficial on architectures that have built-in support for counting leading zeroes/one (pretty much every major arch): https://godbolt.org/z/8rh8183Ys

A further optimization would be to make this a lookup in a table, which completely eliminates branching:
```cpp
static constexpr unsigned char table[] { 1, 0, 2, 3, 4 };
int leading_ones = std::countl_one(*lead_it);
return leading_ones > 4 ? 0 : table[leading_ones];
```
Then compactify that table into an integer and you get:
```cpp
constexpr int sequence_length(char8_t c)
{
    constexpr auto lookup = 0x43201;
    const int leading_ones = std::countl_one(static_cast<unsigned char>(c));
    return leading_ones > 4 ? 0 : (lookup >> (leading_ones * 4)) & 0xf;
}
```

I am implementing a custom error handling strategy for converting from UTF-16 to UTF-8. My raw bytes are held in a `std::string`.

I naively attempted to iterate this `std::string` by using `next16`. This fails since the iteration under `next16` now iterates single bytes instead of pairs.

```cpp
TEST(Foo, bar) {
  using namespace std::string_literals;
  std::string abc = "a\0b\0c\0"s;
  EXPECT_EQ(abc.size(), 6); // Precondition.

  auto &&x = abc;

  std::u16string abc16;
  const auto end = x.end();
  for (auto it = x.begin(); it < end;) {
    auto ch = utf8::next16(it, end);
    utf8::append16(ch, abc16);
  }

  EXPECT_TRUE(is_valid(abc16.begin(), abc16.end())); // Precondition.
  EXPECT_EQ(utf16to8(abc16), "abc"s); // FAIL.
}
```

With the right warnings enabled this raises a sign-conversion warning in the bowels of utfcpp. I however naively expected that `next16` would already pick the right iteration strategy (it could in principle detect the sizes of the values behind the `word_iterator` passed to `next16`, but does not).

I get the correct behavior if I additionally wrap the string in a `u16string_view` which ensure the iterator advances like expected by `next16`.

```cpp
auto x = std::u16string_view{reinterpret_cast<char16_t *>(abc.data()),
                             abc.size() / 2};
```

I think it would be great if utfcpp could either automatically pick the right iteration strategy based on the value type behind its iterators, or at least reject cases where an iterator over values of smaller size is passed than is expected.

As title mentions, checked and unchecked variations of utf16to8 produce different output.
Simple test case:
```
#include <iostream>
#include <format>
#include "utf8.h"

std::string u16_to_u8_unchecked(const std::u16string& u16)
{
	std::string str;
	utf8::unchecked::utf16to8(u16.begin(), u16.end(), std::back_inserter(str));
	return str;
}

int main()
{
	std::u16string u16 = u"Simple test!";

	std::string u8_checked = utf8::utf16to8(u16);
	std::string u8_unchecked = u16_to_u8_unchecked(u16);

	std::cout << std::format("{}\n{}\n", u8_checked, u8_unchecked);
	std::cout << std::format("{} {} {}\n", u8_checked == u8_unchecked, u8_checked.size(), u8_unchecked.size());

	return 0;
}
```
Produces this output:
```
Simple test!
Simple test
false 12 11
```
